backslash.haxe_doc: True if the last directory separator is a backslash, false otherwise.

ext.haxe_doc:
The file extension.
It is separated from the file name by a dot. This dot is not part of the extension.
If the path has no extension, the value is null.

file.haxe_doc:
The file name.
This is the part of the part between the directory and the extension.
If there is no file name, e.g. for ".htaccess" or "/dir/", the value is the empty String "".

dir.haxe_doc:
The directory.
This is the leading part of the path that is not part of the file name and the extension.
Does not end with a / or \ separator.
If the path has no directory, the value is null.

new.haxe_doc:
Creates a new Path instance by parsing [path].
Path information can be retrieved by accessing the dir, file and ext properties.

class.haxe_doc: This class provides a convenient way of working with paths. It supports the common path formats: directory1/directory2/filename.extension directory1\directory2\filename.excention

addNativeLib.haxe_doc: Adds a native library depending on the platform (eg : -swf-lib for Flash)

include.haxe_doc: Include for compilation all classes defined in the given package excluding the ones referenced in the ignore list.

exclude.haxe_doc: Exclude a given class or a complete package from being generated.

excludeFile.haxe_doc: Exclude classes listed in an extern file (one per line) from being generated.

patchTypes.haxe_doc: Load a type patch file that can modify declared classes fields types

keep.haxe_doc:
Mark a class (or array of classes) with the metadata @:keep.
Note that this does not imply inclusion of the class(es): If a class is neither referenced nor added via [Compiler.include], it will not be part of the output even if @:keep was added.

setCustomJSGenerator.haxe_doc: Change the default JS output by using a custom generator callback

class.haxe_doc: All these methods can be called for compiler configuration macros.

toString.haxe_doc:
Converts type [c] to a human-readable String representation.
The result is guaranteed to be valid haxe code, but there may be differences from the original lexical syntax.

class.haxe_doc: This class provides some utility methods to work with AST-level types. It is best used through 'using haxe.macro.ComplexTypeTools' syntax and then provides additional methods on haxe.macro.Expr.ComplexType instances.

error.haxe_doc: Display a compilation error at the given position in code and abort the current macro call

warning.haxe_doc: Display a compilation warning at the given position in code

resolvePath.haxe_doc: Resolve a filename based on current classpath.

currentPos.haxe_doc: Returns the position at which the macro is called

getLocalClass.haxe_doc: Returns the current class in which the macro is called

getLocalType.haxe_doc: Returns the current type in/on which the macro is called

getLocalMethod.haxe_doc: Returns the name of the method from which the macro was called

getLocalUsing.haxe_doc: Returns classes which are available for "using" where the macro was called

getLocalVars.haxe_doc: Returns local variables accessible where the macro was called

defined.haxe_doc: Tells is the given compiler directive has been defined with -D

definedValue.haxe_doc: Returns the value defined through -D key=value

getType.haxe_doc: Resolve a type from its name.

getModule.haxe_doc: Return the list of types defined in the given compilation unit module

parse.haxe_doc: Parse a constructed string into the corresponding expression.

parseInlineString.haxe_doc: Parse a string contained into source code into the corresponding expression. Errors positions are reported within this string

makeExpr.haxe_doc: Build an expression corresponding to the given runtime value. Only basic types + enums are supported.

signature.haxe_doc: Quickly build an hashed MD5 signature for any given value

onGenerate.haxe_doc: Set a callback function that will return all the types compiled before they get generated.

onTypeNotFound.haxe_doc: Set a callback function that will be called when a type cannot be found.

typeof.haxe_doc: Evaluate the type a given expression would have in the context of the current macro call.

toComplexType.haxe_doc: Returns the ComplexType corresponding to the given Type.

unify.haxe_doc: Returns true if t1 and t2 unify, false otherwise

follow.haxe_doc: Follow all typedefs to reach the actual real type

getPosInfos.haxe_doc: Get the informations stored into a given position.

makePosition.haxe_doc: Build a position with the given informations.

addResource.haxe_doc: Add or modify a resource that will be accessible with haxe.Resource api.

getBuildFields.haxe_doc: Returns the list of fields for the current type inside the build macro.

defineType.haxe_doc: Define a new type based on the given definition.

getTypedExpr.haxe_doc: Return the raw expression corresponding to the given typed expression.

registerModuleDependency.haxe_doc: Manually add a dependency between a module and a third party file : make sure the module gets recompiled (if it was cached) in case the extern file has been modified as well.

registerModuleReuseCall.haxe_doc: Add a macro call to perform in case the module is reused by the compilation cache.

onMacroContextReused.haxe_doc: Register a callback function that will be called everytime the macro context cached is reused with a new compilation. This enable to reset some static vars since the code might have been changed. If the callback returns false, the macro context is discarded and another one is created.

class.haxe_doc: This is an API that can be used by macros implementations.
This error can be used to handle or produce compilation errors in macros.

toString.haxe_doc:
Converts expression [e] to a human-readable String representation.
The result is guaranteed to be valid haxe code, but there may be differences from the original lexical syntax.

class.haxe_doc:
This class provides some utility methods to work with expressions. It is best used through 'using haxe.macro.ExprTools' syntax and then provides additional methods on haxe.macro.Expr instances.
While mainly intended to be used in macros, it works in non-macro code as well.
This class provides functions on expression arrays for convenience. For a detailed reference on each method, see the documentation of ExprTools.
The actual macro implemented for Std.format

types.haxe_doc: all the types that were compiled by haXe

setTypeAccessor.haxe_doc: define the JS code that gets generated when a class or enum is accessed in a typed expression

quoteString.haxe_doc: quote and escape the given string constant

The haXe Remoting Socket Protocol is composed of serialized string exchanges. Each string is prefixed with a 2-chars header encoding the string size (up to 4KB) and postfixed with the \0 message delimiting char. A request string is composed of the following serialized values : - the boolean true for a request - an array of strings representing the object+method path - an array of parameters A response string is composed of the following serialized values : - the boolean false for a response - a serialized value representing the result Exceptions are serialized with [serializeException] so they will be thrown immediatly when they are unserialized.

setReturnCode.haxe_doc: Set the HTTP return code. Same remark as setHeader.

getPostData.haxe_doc: Returns all the POST data. POST Data is always parsed as being application/x-www-form-urlencoded and is stored into the getParams hashtable. POST Data is maximimized to 256K unless the content type is multipart/form-data. In that case, you will have to use [getMultipart] or [parseMultipart] methods.

getMultipart.haxe_doc: Get the multipart parameters as an hashtable. The data cannot exceed the maximum size specified.

parseMultipart.haxe_doc: Parse the multipart data. Call [onPart] when a new part is found with the part name and the filename if present and [onData] when some part data is readed. You can this way directly save the data on hard drive in the case of a file upload.

flush.haxe_doc: Flush the data sent to the client. By default on Apache, outgoing data is buffered so this can be useful for displaying some long operation progress.

getMethod.haxe_doc: Get the HTTP method used by the client. This api requires Neko 1.7.1+

logMessage.haxe_doc: Write a message into the web server log file. This api requires Neko 1.7.1+

DEFAULT_BUFSIZE.haxe_doc: Each client has an associated buffer. This is the initial buffer size which is set to 128 bytes by default.

MAX_BUFSIZE.haxe_doc: Each client has an associated buffer. This is the maximum buffer size which is set to 64K by default. When that size is reached and some data can't be processed, the client is disconnected.

run.haxe_doc: Run the server. This function should never return.

onError.haxe_doc: Called when an error occured. This enable you to log the error somewhere. By default the error is displayed using [trace].

processClientData.haxe_doc: This method is called when some data has been readed into a Client buffer. If the data can be handled, then you can return the number of bytes handled that needs to be removed from the buffer. It the data can't be handled (some part of the message is missing for example), returns 0.

clientWrite.haxe_doc: This method can be used instead of writing directly to the socket. It ensures that all the data is correctly sent. If an error occurs while sending the data, no exception will occur but the client will be gracefully disconnected.

clientDisconnected.haxe_doc: This method is called after a client has been disconnected.

update.haxe_doc: The [update] method is called after each socket event has been processed or when [updateTime] has been reached. It can be used to perform time-regular tasks such as pings. By default [updateTime] is set to one second.

closeConnection.haxe_doc: Closes the client connection and removes it from the client List.

listenCount.haxe_doc: This is the value of number client requests that the server socket listen for. By default this number is 10 but can be increased for servers supporting a large number of simultaneous requests.

new.haxe_doc: Creates a server instance. The [newData] methods must return the data associated with the Client.

class.haxe_doc: This class enables you to quickly create a custom server that can serve several clients in parallel. This server is using a single thread and process so the server itself processing is not parallel. Non-blocking sockets are used to ensure that a slow client does not block the others.

loadModule.haxe_doc: Loads a Module with the given name. If [loader] is defined, this will be this Module loader, else this loader will be inherited. When loaded this way, the module is directly executed.

loadPrimitive.haxe_doc: Loads a neko primitive. By default, the name is of the form [library@method]. The primitive might not be used directly in haXe since some of the Neko values needs an object wrapper in haXe.

backupCache.haxe_doc: Change the cache value and returns the old value. This can be used to backup the loader cache and restore it later.

setCache.haxe_doc: Set a module in the loader cache.

getCache.haxe_doc: The default loader contains a cache of already loaded modules. It's ensuring that the same module does not get loaded twice when circular references are occuring. The same module can eventually be loaded twice but with different names, for example with two relatives paths reprensenting the same file, since the cache is done on a by-name basic.

addPath.haxe_doc: Adds a directory to the search path. See [getPath]

getPath.haxe_doc: The default loader contains a search path in its [path] field. It's a linked list of Neko strings that is a parsed version of the [NEKOPATH]. This path is used to lookup for modules and libraries.

class.haxe_doc:
Loaders can be used to dynamicly load Neko primitives stored in NDLL libraries.
Loaders can be used to dynamicly load other Neko modules (.n bytecode files). Modules are referenced by names. To lookup the corresponding bytecode file, the default loader first look in its cache, then eventually adds the .n extension to the name and lookup the bytecode in its path.
Loaders can be used for sandbox security. When a Module is loaded with a given Loader, this loader can manager the module security by filtering which primitives can be loaded by this module or by rewrapping them at loading-time with custom securized versions. Loaders are inherited in loaded submodules.

readBytes.haxe_doc: Reads a module from Bytes using the given Loader. The module is initialized but has not yet been executed.

readPath.haxe_doc: Reads a module from a name and using the specified seach path and loader. The module is initialized but has not yet been executed.

readGlobalsNames.haxe_doc: Extract the globals names from the given module

setExport.haxe_doc: Set a value in the Module export table.

getExports.haxe_doc: Each Module has an export table which can be useful to transfert values between modules.

codeSize.haxe_doc: Returns the codeSize of the Module.

loader.haxe_doc: Returns the Loader that this Module was loaded with.s

sendMessage.haxe_doc: Send a message to the thread queue. This message can be readed by using [readMessage].

select.haxe_doc: Wait until one of the sockets groups is ready for the given operation : [read] contains sockets on which we want to wait for available data to be read, [write] contains sockets on which we want to wait until we are allowed to write some data to their output buffers, [others] contains sockets on which we want to wait for exceptional conditions. [select] will block until one of the condition is met, in which case it will return the sockets for which the condition was true. In case a [timeout] (in seconds) is specified, select might wait at worse until the timeout expires.

setFastSend.haxe_doc: Allows the socket to immediatly send the data when written to its output : this will cause less ping but might increase the number of packets / data size, especially when doing a lot of small writes.

setBlocking.haxe_doc: Change the blocking mode of the socket. A blocking socket is the default behavior. A non-blocking socket will abort blocking operations immediatly by throwing a haxe.io.Error.Blocking value.

waitForRead.haxe_doc: Block until some data is available for read on the socket.

setTimeout.haxe_doc: Gives a timeout after which blocking socket operations (such as reading and writing) will abort and throw an exception.

host.haxe_doc: Return the informations about our side of a connected socket.

peer.haxe_doc: Return the informations about the other side of a connected socket.

accept.haxe_doc: Accept a new connected client. This will return a connected socket on which you can read/write some data.

bind.haxe_doc: Bind the socket to the given host/port so it can afterwards listen for connections there.

shutdown.haxe_doc: Shutdown the socket, either for reading or writing.

listen.haxe_doc: Allow the socket to listen for incoming questions. The parameter tells how many pending connections we can have until they get refused. Use [accept()] to accept incoming connections.

connect.haxe_doc: Connect to the given server host/port. Throw an exception in case we couldn't sucessfully connect.

write.haxe_doc: Write the whole data to the socket output.

read.haxe_doc: Read the whole data available on the socket.

close.haxe_doc: Closes the socket : make sure to properly close all your sockets or you will crash when you run out of file descriptors.

custom.haxe_doc: A custom value that can be associated with the socket. Can be used to retreive your custom infos after a [select]. *

output.haxe_doc: The stream on which you can send data. Please note that in case the output buffer you will block while writing the data, use [setBlocking(false)] or [setTimeout] to prevent that.

input.haxe_doc: The stream on which you can read available data. By default the stream is blocking until the requested data is available, use [setBlocking(false)] or [setTimeout] to prevent infinite waiting.
